  <!-- Introducción de la lección (narrative) -->
  <paragraphs>
    <title><custom ref="narrative-leccion-titulo"/></title>
    <p>[+++++++++++++++]</p>
    <p>In a previous lesson, students arranged objects into arrays and described the arrays in terms of equal groups. In this lesson, students write expressions to represent arrays to further connect arrays and multiplication (MP2).</p>
<p>As students connect arrays to expressions, they may write <m>3\times5</m> or <m>5\times3</m> to represent 3 rows of 5 chairs. This is fine as long as students can correctly describe where the <q>3 rows of 5 chairs</q> are in their array or expression. Keep collecting ideas that arise about commutativity.</p>
  </paragraphs>
  
  <!-- Preguntas de reflexión profesor -->
  <paragraphs>
    <title><custom ref="reflection-quest-titulo"/></title>
    <p>[+++++++++++++++]</p>
    <p>In an upcoming lesson, students will learn about the commutative property of multiplication. What do you notice in their work from today’s lesson that you might leverage in that future lesson?</p>
  </paragraphs>
</introduction>


